<div class="page">
  <h1>Things That Make Me Think</h1>
  <p>Papers, books, and arguments that didn't let go after I closed the tab. Some for class, some by choice — the best ones blur the line.</p>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <div class="section-label">Course Readings — Gaming Seminar SS2026</div>

  <div class="reading">
    <div class="apa">Bogost, I. (2008). The rhetoric of video games. In K. Salen (Ed.), <em>The ecology of games: Connecting youth, games, and learning</em> (pp. 117–140). MIT Press.</div>
    <div class="note">A game's rules make arguments the way a speech uses words. He calls this procedural rhetoric. The McDonald's Videogame doesn't tell you fast food is bad — the mechanics force you into the same corners the industry faces. The argument lives in the system, not the script.</div>
    <div><span class="tag">Procedural Rhetoric</span><span class="tag">Game Studies</span></div>
  </div>

  <div class="reading">
    <div class="apa">Galey, A., &amp; Ruecker, S. (2010). How a prototype argues. <em>Literary and Linguistic Computing</em>, <em>25</em>(4), 405–424. https://doi.org/10.1093/llc/fqq021</div>
    <div class="note">Prototypes aren't demos. They're arguments. A good one is contestable (you can disagree), defensible (it stands on reasoning), and substantive (it says something real). Building things becomes a way of thinking — not just a step after the thinking is done.</div>
    <div><span class="tag">Prototype Theory</span><span class="tag">Digital Humanities</span></div>
  </div>

  <div class="reading">
    <div class="apa">Smith, R. (2013). Serious games 101. In <em>Serious games: Foundations, concepts and practice</em> (STO-EN-MSG-115, pp. 4-1–4-12). NATO Science and Technology Organization.</div>
    <div class="note">A practical history of serious games, from military sims to health and education. The useful distinction: serious games aren't games with a message bolted on — the learning sits in the mechanics, not the wrapper. The edutainment trap is real and well-documented here.</div>
    <div><span class="tag">Serious Games</span><span class="tag">History</span></div>
  </div>
